# Project Conventions

## Stack
- Python 3.12+ / Flask / PostgreSQL / Redis / React + Next.js / TailwindCSS

## Backend Architecture (Flask)
- Prefer an application factory (`create_app`) and blueprint-based modules
- Keep route handlers thin; move business logic to `services/` or domain modules
- Validate request payloads with Pydantic/Marshmallow schemas
- Use SQLAlchemy (ORM + Alembic migrations), avoid raw SQL unless justified
- Keep configuration environment-driven (`.env`, secret manager, CI secrets)

## Frontend (React/Next.js)
- Prefer Next.js App Router for new features
- Use Server Components by default; mark Client Components only when needed
- Keep UI state local; use React Query/SWR for server state
- Centralize API client logic (`fetch` wrapper, auth headers, error mapping)
- Reuse design system components and Tailwind utility patterns consistently

## Redis
- Use Redis for cache, rate limiting, short-lived sessions, and background queue state
- Enforce key naming convention: `<app>:<env>:<domain>:<id>[:<field>]`
- Set TTL for cache keys by default; avoid unbounded growth
- Prefer pipelining for bulk writes/reads and Lua/transactions for atomic multi-step updates
- Never store secrets or long-term source-of-truth data only in Redis

## API and Contracts
- Version APIs under `/api/v1` and preserve backward compatibility
- Keep OpenAPI 3.1 docs aligned with implemented endpoints
- Standardize error payload shape (`code`, `message`, optional `details`)

## Locale & Time
- Avoid hardcoded user-facing strings; use i18n resources
- Store datetimes in UTC; convert at the boundaries (UI/reporting)

## Deployment
- Container-first deployment with reproducible builds
- Healthcheck endpoints required for app and dependent services
